So you really do encourage the undergraduate to come and... We're trying to place ourselves as the central part of the library for undergraduate and graduate education.

47:33.280 --> 47:33.961
See, that's wonderful.

47:35.062 --> 47:37.465
And much of our work is geared toward that.

47:37.505 --> 47:39.447
And where does this originate from?

47:40.508 --> 47:44.993
It came partly out of the merger of this division.

47:45.033 --> 47:50.860
The Division of Rare Manuscript Collections grew up out of four separate departments.

47:51.278 --> 47:54.903
I came to Cornell as the head of the department of rare books.

47:56.345 --> 48:03.215
The other three were archives and manuscripts, but literary and medieval manuscripts were always in rare books.

48:03.856 --> 48:17.936
The history of science collections, which grew out of the specifications of the particular donor in which the history of science materials were pulled out of the rare book collection and they created their own history of science collection and the Icelandic collection.

48:18.937 --> 48:20.239
We pulled all of them together

48:20.894 --> 48:22.296
We restructured.

48:22.577 --> 48:24.240
When this building was built, we moved in.

48:25.602 --> 48:28.147
And our approach has changed fairly significantly.

48:28.607 --> 48:35.960
The building was designed to allow us to be an active member of the teaching community.

48:37.643 --> 48:39.326
And we built our programs around that.

48:40.348 --> 48:46.378
So public services and public access is probably the primary preoccupation of people in this division.

48:48.097 --> 48:49.158
Were you going to show me something?

48:49.179 --> 48:52.083
Yes, I want to take you to the vault, actually, so you have a chance to see the building.

48:52.824 --> 48:53.565
We're in a rear book.

48:53.785 --> 48:55.007
What do we call this, the rear book room?

48:55.027 --> 48:55.287
Vault.

48:55.347 --> 48:55.848
Vault.

48:56.329 --> 48:59.753
And you're saying that you see... It's actually a vault for a manuscript.

48:59.974 --> 49:00.194
Okay.

49:00.214 --> 49:02.557
And you said you shelve according to size.

49:02.577 --> 49:02.858
Right.

49:02.878 --> 49:06.343
And we have five shelving locations, size locations for books.

49:06.363 --> 49:09.147
Tiny, which is less than 16 centimeters.

49:09.968 --> 49:13.673
A regular, which is in quarto.

49:14.815 --> 49:15.015
Um...

49:15.282 --> 49:18.848
single plus, double plus, triple plus, quadruple plus.

49:18.868 --> 49:20.310
Are they shelved by subject?

49:20.691 --> 49:29.825
They're shelved according to the Library of Congress classification, but there are collections that are shelved independent of the general rare book collection.

49:31.107 --> 49:41.323
They're often referred to as the special collections, and that includes the Dante, the Petrarch, the Shaw, the Witchcraft, and the Wordsworth collections, History of Science,

49:41.624 --> 49:45.930
also has a general history of science collection, but there are several named collections.

49:46.571 --> 49:48.794
Those are mostly due to donor specifications.

49:49.354 --> 49:54.561
The Hill Collection, the same hill that you find in San Diego, for example.

49:55.563 --> 49:59.889
The Adelman Collection, a couple of others in the history of science as well.

49:59.909 --> 50:08.560
So it's a fairly complicated vault, five different shelving locations for each possible named collection.

50:08.700 --> 50:10.703
And you were saying before I put on the machine that

50:12.472 --> 50:25.092
The nature of these stacks is such that you know it's— One would have thought when we left the old rare book vault, you're used to being able to locate material by walking up and down the aisle and just spotting books.

50:25.333 --> 50:35.169
And there was some fear on my part, although I understood the advantage of going to compact shelving, but just sort of a cultural familiarity.

50:35.189 --> 50:37.973
I was afraid of not being able to see my books.

50:38.273 --> 50:41.858
But we don't allow browsing in the rare bunglebee.

50:41.958 --> 50:43.120
No, it makes perfect sense.

50:43.140 --> 50:46.885
It's just for the staff in terms of whether they were happy with it or not.

50:47.306 --> 50:50.790
But actually what it's led to is a much greater familiarity of the collections.

50:50.911 --> 51:03.929
And if you watch people paging books for classes, for example, they're punching buttons with the same kind of knowledge about what aisle to go into as if the aisles were open.

51:04.329 --> 51:07.774
So you actually have a much better sense of your collections even though you can't see the books.

51:08.395 --> 51:13.081
in a much more... But to get in here, you have everything... These are in stations.

51:13.141 --> 51:14.483
There are fixed shelves.

51:14.563 --> 51:16.065
This is fully computerized.

51:16.165 --> 51:18.408
And in between are about eight or nine units.

51:18.428 --> 51:33.408
And so to move them... So it's possible to run eight different aisles at the same time.

51:33.428 --> 51:35.470
Are these designed for Cornell?

51:35.631 --> 51:36.732
These are...

51:37.049 --> 51:41.155
They were modified for Cornell to meet our shelving specifications.

51:41.175 --> 51:43.619
So these are items that are available.

51:43.939 --> 51:44.180
Yes.

51:44.280 --> 51:48.967
This is Montel Shelving, which is a French-Canadian firm.

51:48.987 --> 51:50.570
We're French firm.

51:50.590 --> 51:52.813
I think French-Canadian.

51:54.976 --> 51:56.719
We've had no problems with it whatsoever.

51:56.779 --> 51:57.480
It's smooth.

51:57.560 --> 51:58.361
It doesn't lurch.

52:00.144 --> 52:00.645
It's beautiful.

52:00.825 --> 52:02.668
It reacts when you want it to.

52:02.935 --> 52:11.345
It has a built-in feature at the end of the day in which all the shelves move apart equidistant from each other so that everything can breathe overnight, so they're not locked away.

52:11.365 --> 52:12.606
And that's done automatically.

52:12.626 --> 52:14.689
That's done automatically.

52:14.709 --> 52:19.575
And it allows a very immediate access to the collection.

52:20.255 --> 52:23.019
Remember all these big folios standing?

52:23.039 --> 52:23.960
Yeah, yeah.

52:23.980 --> 52:29.446
The flat folios are shelved in the fixed shelving units where the motor is actually.

52:29.466 --> 52:30.968
Do you have any pictures of this stuff?

52:31.133 --> 52:33.957
Actually, there's a photograph in the brochure, I think.

52:34.658 --> 52:35.700
Quite a nice contrast.

52:36.020 --> 52:39.285
I'm sure there are incunables in here.

52:39.325 --> 52:41.448
Yeah, there are incunables everywhere here.

52:41.989 --> 52:53.186
Actually, what is going on here that these are all... This is probably part of... Yes, this is part of the French Revolution project, which also included conservation of all the materials.

52:53.366 --> 53:00.617
So part of going through the French Revolution collection was to take all the freestanding pamphlets that are scattered about

53:01.120 --> 53:16.559
deacidify them, put them into passive bindings, retaining the original sewing, so if it's stab sewn, we retain it, and redoing the bindings.

53:16.679 --> 53:17.881
All this work is done here?

53:17.901 --> 53:19.763
All this work is done by John Dean's operation.

53:19.823 --> 53:22.226
That's quite impressive.

53:22.246 --> 53:24.169
It's worthy of a fine bindery, isn't it?

53:24.689 --> 53:26.451
And these are cranked.

53:26.471 --> 53:28.234
Cranked out downstairs.

53:28.594 --> 53:29.355
Just cranked out.

53:29.572 --> 53:36.121
And those poor kids did 18,000 French pamphlets all in those pale blue papers.

53:36.141 --> 53:37.783
I'm sure they're quite sick of that color by now.

53:38.845 --> 53:41.829
But, you know, I'm quite lucky as a curator.

53:41.849 --> 53:46.255
It's unusual to find a rare book vault that can look like this consistently.

53:47.697 --> 53:49.780
It's so immaculate, too, I have to say.

53:49.800 --> 53:55.308
Well, that's one of my particular things.

53:55.328 --> 53:55.528
All right.

53:57.162 --> 54:02.910
I saw the collections run all the way down to about the middle of the vault.

54:03.711 --> 54:06.615
And you told me earlier how many printed books you have?

54:06.635 --> 54:08.237
About 300,000 printed volumes.

54:08.257 --> 54:09.679
And they're largely all down here?

54:10.080 --> 54:13.204
All the printed collections are in the vault.

54:13.224 --> 54:13.445
Right here.

54:13.465 --> 54:19.373
A good portion of the archival collections are in remote storage, those that are lesser used.

54:21.412 --> 54:30.267
The advantage also of coming into the building is you can design your shelving to meet your needs, so the Audubon has its own shelving.

54:30.287 --> 54:33.673
These are the Audubon's four volumes.

54:34.654 --> 54:39.683
And this is all part of the Hill collection, the Ornithology collection.

54:39.703 --> 54:40.344
Whose was this?

54:40.384 --> 54:42.387
This must have come as a gift at some point.

54:42.467 --> 54:43.088
Yes, it did.

54:45.172 --> 54:47.115
That's all right.

54:47.956 --> 54:49.539
I better verify that.

54:49.639 --> 54:51.784
They didn't belong to me when I first came here.

54:51.804 --> 54:54.769
They've come to me from the History of Science collection.

54:55.070 --> 54:56.332
Ah, well.

54:56.393 --> 54:57.555
Someone who speaks better of it.

54:58.757 --> 55:01.923
We're looking at several million dollars' worth of books, easily.

55:02.184 --> 55:02.424
Here?

55:02.725 --> 55:03.587
No, just those four.

55:03.747 --> 55:04.288
Just those four.

55:04.328 --> 55:05.530
I was going to say, this wall.

55:05.551 --> 55:06.613
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

55:06.633 --> 55:07.855
Just those four, I mean.

55:08.240 --> 55:09.782
No, no, no.

55:09.862 --> 55:16.109
I was talking about one, two, three, four, five.

55:16.469 --> 55:17.410
Yeah.

55:17.430 --> 55:22.215
When we want to expand, this is apropos of the accessioning question.

55:22.556 --> 55:24.298
This is the sort of dead poet's corner.

55:24.358 --> 55:34.409
This will give you a sense of, I think we probably have now the world's largest collection of Lafayette busts.

55:34.429 --> 55:35.530
All lying...

55:36.758 --> 55:38.219
supine on the shelves.

55:38.620 --> 55:41.182
We're in the middle of an NEH project on Icelandic.

55:41.282 --> 55:46.347
We're converting an old classification scheme to a new one and putting them online.

55:46.387 --> 55:56.938
This is as a prelude to the digital project that Saganet, that we were developing, and so this is part of that project going on right now as we speak.

55:57.939 --> 55:59.380
No, no, you're fine.

55:59.520 --> 55:59.961
You're fine.

56:00.301 --> 56:01.942
Asia Rare is also shoved down here.

56:01.982 --> 56:06.647
One of the necessities of

56:06.863 --> 56:13.610
Moving was to create an arrangement of manuscripts where everything was numbered and rare.

56:15.132 --> 56:15.673
Barcoded.

56:15.953 --> 56:23.722
Barcoded for circulation with an inventory location as well so that we know where they sit on the shelf at all times.

56:23.742 --> 56:29.648
Kroc Library, file 224, face number A, shelf number three, position A.

56:31.670 --> 56:39.700
I've actually devised a shelving system dissimilar to that for my own books at home because I have books in them.

56:39.720 --> 56:41.462
It's actually a very old English system.

56:41.482 --> 56:42.183
Well, it works.

56:42.203 --> 56:43.605
Yeah, you just call it something.

56:43.945 --> 56:49.452
Downstairs Library, Case 1, Shelp 3.

56:49.952 --> 56:53.897
It's no different than working in any of the reference rooms in Oxford.

56:53.917 --> 56:54.618
We're all based on that.

56:54.638 --> 56:56.580
Look at all the Lafayette stuff.

56:56.600 --> 56:58.423
Lafayette is a very interesting story.

56:58.443 --> 56:58.723
That's huge.

56:58.940 --> 57:01.423
The Joyce collection is equally impressive that way.

57:02.364 --> 57:06.850
Tom Staley would love to have that, wouldn't he?

57:06.870 --> 57:08.432
I'm not sure.

57:08.452 --> 57:12.017
I haven't asked him that.

57:12.037 --> 57:13.299
I'm sure he would.

57:13.879 --> 57:15.121
I'm just teasing.

57:15.501 --> 57:17.144
Anything, Joyce, you can just assume.

57:18.786 --> 57:27.597
You count up a number of people who own notebooks from the first draft of Ulysses, which Cornell has, but there are other institutions that have them as well.

57:27.982 --> 57:29.924
This would be one interesting jigsaw puzzle.

57:29.944 --> 57:36.070
And in fact, I think this would be ultimately, this would be the penultimate digital project.

57:36.210 --> 57:42.476
Get all these institutions to agree that we will all digitize our Joyce notebooks and put them up as a single publication on the web.

57:43.557 --> 57:47.481
Now, why do you think they would not agree to... No, because they're such prized possessions.

57:47.701 --> 57:49.623
We spent a lot of... In Texas in particular.

57:49.663 --> 57:51.224
In Texas in particular, exactly.

57:51.825 --> 57:54.107
I mean, anyway, the literature Xerox or...

57:54.526 --> 57:58.070
We're not based on that model.

57:58.471 --> 58:02.336
We do the photocopying for people that we do photocopy.

58:02.356 --> 58:09.605
We're really much more involved, I think, in a research and instructional mode than other institutions will be.

58:10.225 --> 58:14.050
We're fairly generous with the materials, too, within the reason of conservation.

58:14.751 --> 58:22.761
You can tell when we move into the archival section that the shelving changes to four-posts as opposed to cantilever, and it's designed to accommodate

58:23.348 --> 58:25.030
through boxes across.

58:26.712 --> 58:30.597
The same compact shelving that's now moving tons of paper.

58:31.138 --> 58:32.239
It's very impressive.

58:32.760 --> 58:33.821
And they just glide along.

58:35.143 --> 58:37.706
Have you seen the Harvard Depository setup?

58:37.766 --> 58:43.814
We're actually, the remote storage thing, we're mimicking that here at Cornell, the one with the huge tower.

58:44.735 --> 58:47.719
They're currently breaking ground for that right now.

58:47.759 --> 58:51.043
The next remote storage is based on that same system here.

58:51.665 --> 59:00.236
and is being built to environmental specifications for rare books and manuscripts, so we can send materials there.

59:00.656 --> 59:07.104
The goal so far has been not to let the books go out, because archival materials tend to travel a little bit more safely.

59:07.124 --> 59:11.009
And Harvard does keep its archival stuff at the outside.

59:11.049 --> 59:12.571
So ours has been based on usage.

59:12.651 --> 59:16.796
If a collection is called in too often, we actually exchange it with something else involved.

59:16.816 --> 59:20.220
So we do have flexibility because we're online.

59:20.555 --> 59:22.577
As they do as well, actually.

59:22.597 --> 59:24.919
It's called for, then they'll leave it in Cambridge.

59:25.299 --> 59:26.200
Right.

59:26.220 --> 59:32.426
So the difference is that ours is only at the edge of the apple with orchards on campus, it's not on the other.

59:32.446 --> 59:35.109
They share space with the primate center.

59:35.129 --> 59:39.393
They have monkeys on one side and books on the other.

59:39.813 --> 59:47.220
Don't think I'm not going to get that into the next book, one way or another.

59:47.808 --> 59:58.383
And you can have a sense of, I'm sorry, I'm trying very hard to meet the Harvard standards, but I just don't think I can match that.

59:58.924 --> 01:00:01.107
More examples of John Dean's work.

01:00:01.247 --> 01:00:09.078
We have the ability, we're very fortunate here, as curators, we can send materials to conservation and they come back immediately in boxes.

01:00:09.098 --> 01:00:14.946
So these are actually fan-fold manuscripts from the Asia Rare collection.

01:00:16.647 --> 01:00:35.972
many of which are paper mache with bits of water glass and very nicely boxed so that we can deal with our materials intelligently.

01:00:36.012 --> 01:00:37.634
Second part of the vault?

01:00:37.654 --> 01:00:38.014
I'm sorry.

01:00:38.034 --> 01:00:39.055
Second part of the vault?

01:00:39.075 --> 01:00:43.761
Yes, which is on the mezzanine level, but it's the very top floor.

01:00:44.943 --> 01:00:45.844
It's a half level.

01:00:46.651 --> 01:00:50.295
And that holds all the flat material, mostly map cases.

01:00:51.337 --> 01:00:53.880
Actually, this is a perfect example of what I was just telling you about.

01:00:53.940 --> 01:00:57.804
These are trucks that are left over from presentations from last week.

01:00:57.824 --> 01:01:02.009
This is a course called Cornell 101, which deals with the history of the university.

01:01:02.170 --> 01:01:03.732
And that's the charter of the university.

01:01:03.752 --> 01:01:05.754
Yes, the actual charter of the university.

01:01:05.774 --> 01:01:13.283
This was a course on... This was a presentation to the Board of Trustees, which included...

01:01:13.803 --> 01:01:17.989
an overview of how we use materials in the instruction program.

01:01:18.010 --> 01:01:19.692
And these are largely maps and charts.

01:01:19.792 --> 01:01:28.466
Well, actually, this also includes the Gettysburg Address, the Emancipation Proclamation, and the Thirteenth Amendment, all in the original documents, and original manuscript.

01:01:28.546 --> 01:01:32.292
Le Brasier's notebook for the discovery of the formula for water.

01:01:32.672 --> 01:01:34.776
Which you're holding in your hands right now.

01:01:34.796 --> 01:01:39.863
And signed by LaFosse and the major scientists of the period.

01:01:40.244 --> 01:01:41.346
These are the Joyce notebooks.

01:01:41.987 --> 01:01:42.207
Ah.

01:01:42.811 --> 01:01:48.598
The reason they're free like this is that... That's a little tactile kick for me.

01:01:48.618 --> 01:01:53.164
This is from the Norisica chapter of Ulysses.

01:01:53.224 --> 01:02:01.534
So this was a very high-end discussion for the Board of Trustees that included a variety of materials for a portfolio.

01:02:01.634 --> 01:02:04.578
Cornell has all... And as we speak, they're on these little trucks.

01:02:04.598 --> 01:02:06.200
They're meant to be reshelled.

01:02:06.220 --> 01:02:07.141
They're on the way to be reshelled.

01:02:07.161 --> 01:02:08.903
We're looking at precious items in a...

01:02:09.423 --> 01:02:10.584
That's wonderful.

01:02:10.644 --> 01:02:15.108
This was the freshman course on the Arthurian legend in Chaucer.

01:02:15.188 --> 01:02:21.153
It includes Mallory, Nuremberg Chronicle, medieval manuscripts as examples, chain book.

01:02:21.854 --> 01:02:22.635
Where's the chain book?

01:02:22.975 --> 01:02:24.056
The chain book is actually right here.

01:02:26.278 --> 01:02:27.078
Still have a chain on it?

01:02:27.339 --> 01:02:29.200
Yeah, yeah.

01:02:29.220 --> 01:02:29.861
Oh, that's great.

01:02:30.101 --> 01:02:31.102
Fabulous, isn't it?

01:02:31.162 --> 01:02:31.943
Yeah, that's wonderful.

01:02:32.003 --> 01:02:32.924
I've only seen one other.

01:02:32.984 --> 01:02:33.945
My first.

01:02:34.045 --> 01:02:35.326
Is that right?

01:02:35.346 --> 01:02:36.207
Yeah, my first.

01:02:36.287 --> 01:02:37.928
I've had three collections.

